anyOf.description: A refund is the 'reflection' of a stripe refund, we keep track of it by parsing stripe webhook events. We have a periodic function (processBatch from RefundsController) that process new refunds every now and then. Note that every timestamp (except for creationTimestamp) can be null and has a corresponding boolean (eg: 'successTimestamp' is pairedwith the 'succeeded' boolean). If a refund is still unprocessed (not emitted), we have emissionTimestamp null (and other timestamps null as well). When a refund is emitted, an email is sent to the user (from stripe) and emissionTimestamp is set. When the user accepts the refund and the money is transfered correctly, successTimestamp is set. If the user forgets to accept the refund, the refund gets cancelled and cancelationTimestamp is set, a new refund will be initiated. If the refund fails for any reason, failureTimestamp is set. This particular type of refund (SECURITY_DEPOSIT) is linked to an auction, so an 'auctionSubscription' is added to the response.

A refund is the 'reflection' of a stripe refund, we keep track of it by parsing stripe webhook events. We have a periodic function (processBatch from RefundsController) that process new refunds every now and then. Note that every timestamp (except for creationTimestamp) can be null and has a corresponding boolean (eg: 'successTimestamp' is pairedwith the 'succeeded' boolean). If a refund is still unprocessed (not emitted), we have emissionTimestamp null (and other timestamps null as well). When a refund is emitted, an email is sent to the user (from stripe) and emissionTimestamp is set. When the user accepts the refund and the money is transfered correctly, successTimestamp is set. If the user forgets to accept the refund, the refund gets cancelled and cancelationTimestamp is set, a new refund will be initiated. If the refund fails for any reason, failureTimestamp is set. This type of refund (CASH_BALANCE) means there were extra funds in the user cash balance.
